The reason Arthur Jones chose Casey Viator as the bodybuilder to test the Nautilus exercise machines on is his name imo, "Viator" has this resonance with "aviator", reminiscent of piloting experimental aircraft, Charles Lindbergh and Dr. Goddard testing rockets at Roswell, etc.

"Viator" is an insanely smooth name. You just intuitively imagine the man carrying it to be this test pilot Dyna-Soar rider on anabolic steroids operating a Space Shuttle, like a name out of the 22nd century. Retrofuturism. Should be used as a surname too. Viator.

Someone on /fit/ made a post about how Norwegian bodybuilder Gunnar Rosbo used to drink 750 ml of vodka and 24 beers the day before a show, online you can find out anecdotes how he spent all his time outside the gym at bars eating hot dogs and mash potatoes and drinking beer.

Always ordered double shots, drank entire cabinets of liquor, took smoke breaks between sets at the gym and just spent all his time drinking beer and eating hot dogs. Old school style alcoholic. Norwegians are crazy.

The idea that the intestine is a source of stress and disease eventually leading to the death of the organism is basically the central thread of European medicine. Pavlov treated everyone with broths and studied the reflexes related to the intestine. Dr. Walter Alvarez, Ray Peat.

It's wild that this idea basically starts from Hippocrates and just continues with Paracelsus who talked about gout as tartar from the intestines and formulated herbal digestive bitters, Metchnikoff later wanted to populate the gut with milk kefir-y bacteria to limit stress, etc.

It basically started with "Gigachad dialogues" where these characters like Soyjak are presented having a humorous conversation but then people started using it on its own as a "Gigachad quote" and it morphed into a way to create ironic distance between what you say and yourself
